If we next examine the foundation of necessity, it will
appear to be equally destitute of authority, as the other
distinction.
... And the answer is ready in the mouth of every one,
that if the crown is the judge of that necessity,
the p ow er is unlimit e d; b ec au se the discretion of
the princes and his couneil may apply it to any
instance whatever: and so discretion degenerates
in despotism.
